<HEAD>Stolen Mail Box Nets Thieves More Than $1,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHOREWOOD HILLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police say robbers netted more than $ 1,000 by putting an out-of-order sign on a bank's night depository that directed business people to put their bank bags in a stolen mailbox nearby. At least three business people deposited their receipts in the stolen <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service drop box Saturday at the front entrance to the <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> branch in <LOCATION> Shorewood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, police in this Madison suburb said Monday. Thieves dropped off the 200-pound mailbox at the bank after it closed Saturday and removed it that night or Sunday morning, Detective <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuschel </PERSON> said. He said more than one robber and a truck or van was probably needed to handle the mailbox. Police learned of the robbery after an empty bank bag was found floating Sunday afternoon in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mendota </LOCATION> at Madison. The stolen mailbox was found nearby.
