<HEAD>Barry Chase Named Vice President for Programming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> was named vice president for programming Tuesday for the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the national program service said. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> is vice president for news and public affairs at <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION>, and with his new title his duties will expand to include overall supervision of <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION> liaison with producers in the development and production of programs, <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> was named director of news and public affairs programming in 1978, and became vice president in 1984. At the same time, <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> announced that <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fergenson </PERSON> <PERSON> Petroff </PERSON> has been named vice president, promotion and advertising at <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION>. She had been director of national program promotion. PBS is a private, non-profit corporation that does not produce programming but gets shows from 334 member stations, independent producers and international TV-film distributors. It directs program acquisition on behalf of the member stations.
